  }), mdx("h2", null, "Internet of Things(IOT)"), mdx("p", null, "The Internet of Things, or IoT is the concept of connecting any device (if it has on/off switch) to the internet and the other connected devices to share data and perform specific action. Thanks to the arrival of super cheap computer chips and the ubiquity of wireless networks, it\u2019s possible to turn anything, from something small as a pill to big as aeroplane, kitchen appliances, thermostat, smart microwaves which helps to cook food automatically based on timer, into a part of IoT. Connecting all these different devices and when adding sensors to them adds a level of digital intelligence which enables them to communicate in real-time without involving any human interactions ", "[1][2]", "."), mdx("h2", null, "Data Generated by IoT"), mdx("p", null, "Any physical object can be turned into an IoT device by attaching it to a smart sensor. By 2025, there will be 35 billion ", "[3]", " IoT devices connecting to the web which is forecasted to create 79.4 ", "[4]", " Zettabytes of data. It has been roughly calculated by The Atlantic that to hold a Zettabyte we need 1000 data centers which is a lot of data and to process all these we also need to be equipped with modern technology. There is plethora of ways how IoT is generating data. We are surrounded by these devices which has become an integral part of our day to life and many businesses are growing based of IoT devices."), mdx("h2", null, "Brief History of IoT"), mdx("p", null, "The concept of devices connected with each other itself dates back in 1832 when the first electromagnetic telegraph was designed. However, the true form of IoT research has begun with the form of world wide web in 1960s. Interestingly, Coca-Cola vending machine situated at Carnegie Melon University and operated by local programmers was the first connected device made. In the late 1990s there has been significant number of inventions done by researchers, but the true significa