    parentName: "ul"
  }, "Cloud Computing: The access of cloud computing has been an important factor for both businesses and general people to access the cloud and host the data to be shared by different infrastructure and communicate with each other. People can focus more on the business logic rather than maintaining the servers."), mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ul"
  }, "Machine learning and analytics: Businesses can gather insights faster and more easily by the help of machine learning and analytics along with access to various data sources that are available to us because of IoT devices."), mdx("li", {
    parentName: "ul"
  }, "Artificial Intelligence: Advances in neural networks have brought NLP to IoT devices (Alexa, Cortana, Siri) and made them affordable and appealing for daily life.")), mdx("p", null, "Across the IoT, devices create data that is sent to the main application to consume and used based on the business need. Depending on the device, network and power consumption restraints, data can be sent on real-time, or send in batches of interval or it can be saved locally. However, the real value is restored from the order which data was created. Unless it maintains this feature, it will lose the very aim of the application itself. Whether it is saved in real-time or in time series, traditional way of storing data can be costlier for the businesses. NoSQL framework like Apache Cassandra is better fit for storing IoT data. Due to the volume of write request an IoT devices will make, which Cassandra is capable of even with millions of IoT devices putting write request. Traditional databases have a primary-replica arrangement, where the lead database server will handle all the transactions and synchronously pass them along to other servers if required. This leads to problems in the event of an outage or server failure, as a new primary must be put into place leading to a potential data loss."), mdx("p", null, "For properly configured distributed database systems like Cassandra, there is no primary server that is in charge; each node within a cluster can handle transactions as they come in, and the full record is maintained over time. Even if a server fails, or a node is removed due to loss of network connectivity, the rest of the cluster can continue to process data as it comes in. For time-series data, this is especially valuable as it means that there should be no loss of data in the list of transactions over time."), mdx("h2", null, "Processing IoT Data"), mdx("p", null, "Data processing is a must step in data analytics dashboards or applications. It is said that about 80% of 